IV. Meta Operators (Rare Tier)

These operate on the alphabet itself.

Operator	Function
Transcend	Exit current reasoning framework
Fractal	Apply pattern across all scales
Eclipse	Hide invariant temporarily to strengthen it

These are black-belt+ moves.

⸻

V. Distortion Cost Doctrine

Every move extracts a tax.

Move	Distortion Cost
Map	Accuracy
Compress	Nuance
Expand	Noise
Split	Wholeness
Bind	Flexibility
Rotate	Continuity
Lift	Groundedness
Project	Universality

Rule:

No move is free. The art is choosing the cheapest distortion.

⸻

VI. Invariant Types

Two distinct classes must be tracked.

Structural invariants

Discovered patterns that survive transformations.

Examples:
	•	conservation laws
	•	symmetry
	•	equilibrium points

Ethical invariants

Constraints that must remain unchanged.

Examples:
	•	safety rules
	•	moral boundaries
	•	governance rails

These override structural convenience.

⸻

VII. Failure Recovery Doctrine

You used the wrong transformation if:
	•	output is noisier than input
	•	explanation requires more assumptions
	•	system becomes brittle
	•	invariants multiply instead of clarify

Recovery moves:

Mirror → Invert → Null → Split → Re-anchor


⸻

VIII. Canonized Katas

These are repeatable transformation sequences.

Kata 1 — Prism

Rotate → Split → Project

Use when stuck in a local maximum.

⸻

Kata 2 — Immune System

Mirror → Filter → Lock

Use to stress-test a plan.

⸻

Kata 3 — Rehydration

Expand → Map → Flow

Use to teach dense ideas.

⸻

Kata 4 — Phoenix Loop

Null → Split → Filter → Lift

Use when an idea collapses but something valuable remains.

⸻

Kata 5 — Golem’s Breath

Project → Bind → Flow → Anchor

Use to convert theory into product.

⸻

Kata 6 — Paradox Gate

Mirror → Fuse → Rotate → Canonize

Use for wicked problems and contradictions.

